05706nam a22008415i 9780812299632DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122996327 a10.9783/97808122996322doi  a(DE-B1597)573156  a(OCoLC)1246582827  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aKTW441b.Q85 2021 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a340.1152231 aQuinn, Joanna R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aThin Sympathy :bA Strategy to Thicken Transitional Justice /cJoanna R. Quinn. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tChapter 1. Paving the Way -- tChapter 2. Background and History of Conflict in Uganda -- tChapter 3. Slow Decay or Intentional Neglect? -- tChapter 4. The Thin Sympathy Hypothesis and the Sympathetic Continuum -- tChapter 5. Switching On the Thin Sympathetic Response -- tChapter 6. Manufacturing Thin Sympathy -- tChapter 7. Thickening the Transitional Justice Strategy -- tChapter 8. Bridging the Divide -- tChapter 9. The Strength of Thin Sympathy and Transitional Justice -- tAppendix 1. Ethnocultural Group Representation in Ugandan Population -- tAppendix 2. List of Political Conflicts in Uganda Since Independence -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTransitional justice, commonly defined as the process of confronting the legacies of past human rights abuses and atrocities, often does not produce the kinds of results that are imagined. In multiethnic, divided societies like Uganda, people who have not been directly affected by harm, atrocity, and abuse go about their daily lives without ever confronting what happened in the past. When victims and survivors raise their voices to ask for help, or when plans are announced to address that harm, it is this unaffected population that see such plans as pointless. They complain about what they perceive as the "needless" time and money that will be spent to fix something that they see as unimportant and, ultimately, block any restorative processes.Joanna R. Quinn spent twenty years working in Uganda and uses its particular case as a lens through which she examines the failure of deeply divided societies to acknowledge the past. She proposes that the needed remedy is the development of a very rudimentary understanding—what she calls "thin sympathy"—among individuals in each of the different factions and groups of the other's suffering prior to establishing any transitional justice process. Based on 440 extensive interviews with elites and other thought leaders in government, traditional institutions, faith groups, and NGOs, as well as with women and children throughout the country, Thin Sympathy argues that the acquisition of a basic understanding of what has taken place in the past will enable the development of a more durable transitional justice process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPostwar reconstructionzUganda. 0aRestorative justicezUganda. 0aSympathyxSocial aspectszUganda. 0aTransitional justicezUganda. 4aHuman Rights. 4aPolitical Science/Public Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 